1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. a4 e6 {Recently, this variation
has gained some popularity. Black is mixing up both the Slav and the Queen's
Gambit Accepted.} 6. e4 {The most aggressive reply.} ({The solid alternative} 
6. e3 c5 7. Bxc4 Nc6 8. O-O Be7 9. Qe2 cxd4 10. exd4 O-O {leads to a position
where White has an extra tempo (a2-a4) compared to a normal Queen's Gambit
Accepted. On the other hand, Black gets control over the b4-square and might
use it for a knight transfer Nc6-b4-d5.}) 6... Bb4 7. e5 (7. Bg5 {could
transpose to one of the side lines of the Botvinnik Variation - D44.}) 7... Nd5
8. Bd2 b5 9. Ng5 {A typical knight move, opening the diagonal for the white
queen and also preparing to transfer the knight to the d6-square via e4.
Usually, White plays 9.axb5 at first, forcing Black to part with his
dark-squared bishop. However, the move in the text was obviously prepared by
Maxim Rodshtein at home, since I had played the same line just two rounds
before against Moiseenko.} (9. axb5 Bxc3 10. bxc3 cxb5 11. Ng5 Qe7 12. Qh5 Nd7
13. Be2 Bb7 14. Bg4 $6 (14. Bf3 $142 $44) 14... Nc7 $1 {[%csl Ye6]} 15. O-O h6
16. Bf3 Bxf3 17. Nxf3 O-O $15 {1/2-1/2 Moiseenko,A (2643)-Postny,E (2627)/
Maalot-Tarshiha ISR 2008/The Week in Chess 688 (37)}) 9... Qe7 $146 {This was
an improvisation over the board. I just thought that in the event of 10.axb5
Bxc3 11.bxc3 cxb5 the position would transpose into my game vs Moiseenko, as I
was satisfied with the results of the opening in that game. Previously played
9...Be7 is a bit more solid.} ({A tactical justification of 9.Ng5 is:} 9...
Nxc3 10. bxc3 Bxc3 11. Bxc3 Qxg5 12. axb5 {and Black can't recapture by} cxb5
$2 {in view of} 13. Qf3 $18 {[%csl Ra8]}) (9... Be7 10. Nce4 h6 11. Nf3 O-O 12.
Be2 Nd7 13. O-O a6 14. b3 cxb3 15. Qxb3 Bb7 16. Bd3 c5 17. axb5 axb5 18. Qxb5
Qc7 19. dxc5 Nxc5 20. Nxc5 Bxc5 $11 {1/2-1/2 Eljanov,P (2658)-Drozdovskij,Y 
(2561)/Poltava 2006/CBM 116 (34)}) 10. h4 $6 {This move I didn't expect and I
am still rather sceptical about its value. The point is should White castle
kingside he might well regret this pawn advance.} ({I expected} 10. Qh5 h6 11.
Nge4 {with a very complicated, double-edged position.}) ({Another playable
option is} 10. Be2 {followed by castling. In this case White can count on
long-term compensation as well.}) 10... Nd7 11. Be2 (11. axb5 Bxc3 12. bxc3
cxb5 13. Qb1 a6 14. Nxh7 $2 (14. Ne4 $142 $44) 14... f6 15. Be2 Bb7 16. Bh5+
Kd8 $17 {The Nh7 won't survive.}) 11... c5 $5 {Going for a big mess. Instead,
I could continue developing, but I could not resist the chance to meet play on
the flank (10.h4) by a strike in the centre.} (11... Bb7 12. axb5 Bxc3 13. bxc3
cxb5 14. Qb1 Bc6 {was a worthy alternative.}) 12. Nxb5 $1 {White chooses the
best capture out of numerous options.} (12. axb5 $2 cxd4 13. Nxd5 exd5 $17) (
12. dxc5 Nxe5 13. Nxd5 exd5 14. Bxb4 Nd3+ 15. Kf1 Nxb4 $17) (12. Nxd5 Bxd2+ (
12... exd5 13. Bxb4 cxb4 14. axb5 f6 $15) 13. Qxd2 exd5 14. axb5 cxd4 15. Qxd4
Qxe5 $15) 12... cxd4 13. O-O $2 {I was very surprised by such a cold-blooded
move, which falls short. I expected only the obvious capture of the Pc4.} (13.
Bxc4 Nxe5 14. Bxd5 exd5 15. O-O O-O $11 (15... Bxd2 $6 16. Qxd2 O-O (16... h6
$2 17. Rfe1 $1 hxg5 18. Rxe5 Qxe5 19. Re1 Qxe1+ 20. Qxe1+ $18) 17. Qxd4 $14)
16. Bxb4 Qxb4 17. Nxh7 Re8 (17... Kxh7 $6 18. Qh5+ Kg8 19. Qxe5 $14) 18. Ng5 d3
19. f4 Bg4 20. Qb1 f6 21. fxe5 fxg5 22. Qxd3 Rxe5 {with a dynamically balanced
position.}) 13... d3 14. Bf3 $6 {Objectively, White's position is already bad.
However, a piece sacrifice by 14.Bxb4 would force me to play very precisely.} (
14. Bxb4 $5 Qxb4 $3 {This would be a difficult decision to make, as it seems
very tempting to grab a piece immediatly.} (14... dxe2 $2 15. Qxe2 Qxb4 16.
Nd6+ Ke7 (16... Kf8 17. Ngxf7 Kg8 18. Qh5 g6 19. Qg5 Bb7 20. h5 Nf8 21. Nh6+
Kg7 22. Rad1 $18 {on the next move White will eliminate Black's key defender
by 23.Rxd5 and win.}) 17. Ngxf7 Rf8 18. Qh5 {[%cal Gh5g5]} h6 (18... Nxe5 $2
19. Qg5+ Nf6 20. Nxe5 Kxd6 21. Rfd1+ $1 Nd5 22. Qg3 Kc7 23. Rac1 $18) (18...
Bb7 19. Qg5+ N5f6 20. Nxb7 Rxf7 21. exf6+ gxf6 22. Qb5 Qxb5 23. axb5 $14) 19.
Qg6 Bb7 (19... Ba6 $1 20. Qxg7 Rg8 21. Qh7 N5f6 22. exf6+ Nxf6 23. Qxh6 Bb7 24.
g3 Raf8 25. Qe3 Rxf7 26. Nf5+ Kd7 27. Rfd1+ Bd5 28. Nh6 $14) 20. Ng5 $1 hxg5
21. Qxg5+ N5f6 22. Qxg7+ Kd8 23. Nxb7+ Qxb7 24. exf6 Rxf6 25. Rad1 Rf5 26. h5
$18 {Black is completely tied up and defenseless against the march of the
h-pawn.[%csl Gh5]}) 15. Nd6+ Ke7 16. Ngxf7 (16. Ndxf7 dxe2 17. Qxe2 Rf8 18. Qg4
Qb6 $19) 16... Nxe5 $1 {The point of Black's defence. This strike ruins
White's attacking chain. In the event of 14...dxe2 this would not be possible
because of White's queen on e2 protecting the Pe5.} (16... Rf8 $2 17. Bf3 Rxf7
18. Bxd5 exd5 19. Qh5 Rf8 20. Qg5+ Ke6 21. Rae1 d2 22. Qg4+ Ke7 23. Qg5+ {with
a perpetual check.}) 17. Nxe5 Qxd6 18. Nxc4 dxe2 19. Qxe2 Qf4 $19) 14... O-O $1
{Now my king is safe.} 15. Bxb4 Qxb4 16. Bxd5 exd5 17. Nc7 (17. Qh5 h6 18. Nxf7
Qe7 (18... Rxf7 19. e6 Re7 20. exd7 (20. Qxd5 $2 Nb6 21. Qd8+ Kh7 $19) 20...
Bb7 21. Nc7 Rd8 22. Nxd5 Bxd5 23. Qxd5+ Kh8 $17) 19. Nfd6 Qxe5 20. Qxe5 Nxe5
21. Nc7 Rb8 22. Nxd5 Be6 $19) (17. e6 fxe6 18. Nc7 (18. Nxe6 Rf7 19. Nd8 Rf5
$19) 18... Rb8 19. Ngxe6 Rf6 20. Nxd5 Qd6 21. Nxf6+ Nxf6 22. Ng5 Rxb2 {and two
connected passed pawns should decide the outcome.}) 17... Nxe5 $1 {Very strong.
The rook sacrifice is temporary, Black will trap the knight and get two superb
pawns for the exchange. Meanwhile, the dangerous Pe5 is eliminated and White's
attacking chances evaporate.} (17... Rb8 $2 18. Nxd5 Qc5 19. Qh5 h6 20. Nxf7
Qxd5 (20... Rxf7 $2 21. e6 $18) 21. Nxh6+ gxh6 22. Qg6+ Kh8 23. Qxh6+ {with a
perpetual check.}) 18. Nxa8 Qb8 ({One engine shows the cold-blooded} 18... Qd6
$1 {which would have been even stronger. In that case Black will capture the
Na8 with his rook, keeping the queen in an active position.}) 19. Qe1 (19. Qh5
Bf5 20. Rae1 f6 21. f4 Ng4 $19) 19... h6 20. f4 Ng4 {A great square for the
knight.} 21. Nf3 Qxa8 {Black's position is winning thanks to his connected,
far advanced pawns. White's king is not safe as well, which will become very
apparent later in the game.[%csl Gc4,Gd3,Gd5,Gg4]} 22. Qc3 Bf5 23. Qd4 Qb7 24.
b3 $1 {A good practical chance, but insufficient.} Rc8 25. Rac1 (25. bxc4 dxc4
26. Rab1 Qe4 $19) 25... Qxb3 {After long thought, I came to the conclusion
that I should not exchange queens, but to go for a direct attack against the
white monarch.} (25... Qb6 $6 26. Qxb6 axb6 27. bxc4 dxc4 28. Rc3 {and I
wasn't sure if I could break down White's blockade.}) 26. Qxa7 d2 $1 27. Nxd2
Qg3 {[%csl Rg1]} 28. Nf3 Bd3 29. Qd7 (29. Rfe1 Be4 30. Rf1 Nh2 $1 $19 (30...
Qxf4 $19)) (29. a5 Bxf1 30. Rxf1 Re8 31. Qd7 Nf6 $19 {[%cal Ge8e2]}) 29... Rf8
{29...Rb8 followed by 30...Rb2 was just mating, but in time-trouble there is a
typical human desire to put all the pieces on defended squares.} 30. Rce1 Be4 {
There is no defence against removing the Nf3 followed by Qh2+ and Qh1+. White
resigned.} 0-1

