1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. a4 Na6 6. e4 Bg4 7. Bxc4 Bxf3 8.
gxf3 Nb4 {Already a new move for me. I was only familiar with the following
example:} (8... e6 9. O-O Be7 10. Kh1 O-O 11. Rg1 g6 12. f4 Qa5 13. Qf3 $14 {
1-0 Rogozenko,D-Shirov,A/Germany 2001/CBM 082 ext (46)}) 9. O-O e6 10. Kh1 {
This seems to me the most flexible move here.} (10. a5 {- another popular
alternative, when Black has to castle short, but later on it's much easier for
Black to get his counterplay on the Q-side.}) 10... Qa5 $5 {A relatively new
interpretation of this old line, suddenly Black is going to castle long, which
would lead to very interesting play.} ({White has very promising play after} 
10... Be7 11. Rg1 O-O 12. Bh6 Ne8 13. Qd2 (13. a5) 13... Kh8 14. Be3 a5 15. Rg3
Qd7 16. Rag1 $14 {1-0 Van der Stricht,G-Mohandesi,S/Namur 2006/CBM 113 ext (34)
}) 11. Rg1 $5 $146 (11. Be3 {has been played before.}) 11... h6 {Anticipating
Rg5.[%csl Gg5]} ({Black could have played} 11... O-O-O 12. Be3 {and it seems
to me Black has to play 12...h6 anyway, since} ({It's too early for} 12. Rg5 c5
$1 (12... Qc7 13. Be3 (13. a5 h6 14. Rg1 e5 15. d5 cxd5 16. Bxd5 Nfxd5 17. exd5
Nxd5 18. Nxd5 Qc6 $13)) 13. d5 (13. Bf4 h6) 13... g6 $13) 12... g6 13. Rg5 c5
14. Nb5 $1 {looks pretty dangerous} h6 15. Rg1 a6 16. Qb3 $40) 12. Be3 O-O-O
13. Qb3 Kb8 14. Be2 $1 {In my opinion White's best setup. The B is perfectly
placed on e2, defending the f3-pawn in case of Qh5, while my N is heading to
c4 .} Ne8 {This seems to me very slow, I would prefer to play the more active.}
(14... g5 $5 {following by Nh5-f4.}) 15. Rgc1 Rd7 $1 {A very good defensive
resource.} ({After} 15... g5 16. Nb5 {White's attack looks very unpleasant} Bg7
$140 17. d5 exd5 18. Bc5 $1 Na6 19. Nxa7 $1 $18) 16. Nb5 $1 {Very energetic
and strong.} ({Much worse would have been} 16. Nb1 Bd6 17. Nd2 Qh5 $132) 16...
Qd8 ({If Black accepts the sacrifice} 16... cxb5 17. axb5 Qd8 {I would have a
pleasant choice: either} 18. Bf4+ (18. d5 b6) ({or} 18. Qa4 b6 19. Bf4+ Ka8 20.
Bd2 Nf6 21. Rc4 Nbd5 22. exd5 Nxd5 23. Rc6 $1 (23. f4 Bd6 24. Bf3 Qh4 $1 $132)
23... Be7 (23... Bd6 $140 $2 24. Rxd6 $1 $18 {[%csl Ga7]}) 24. f4 {[%cal Cd8b8,
Ge2f3]}) 18... Bd6 (18... Ka8 19. Qc4 $18 {[%cal Gc4c8]}) 19. Bxd6+ Rxd6 20.
Qxb4 Rxd4 21. Qc5 b6 22. Qa3 Rd7 23. e5 $16 {in both cases with a clear
advantage.[%csl Gb8,Ge8]}) (16... Nc7 17. Nxc7 (17. Na3 Qh5 18. Nc4 f6 19. a5
Nba6) 17... Qxc7 (17... Rxc7 18. Rc4 Na6 19. Bf4) 18. a5 $16 {[%cal Ga1a4]})
17. Na3 {[%cal Ga3c4]} ({I wasn't sure about} 17. d5 cxb5 (17... exd5 $6 18.
Bxa7+ Ka8 19. Qe3 $1 $40) 18. Bxa7+ Kxa7 19. axb5+ Na6 20. bxa6 b6 {with a
complicated game.}) 17... Nc7 $2 {This is already the decisive error. Black
should have stopped a4-a5 at any cost.} (17... a5 $142 18. Nc4 g5 19. Ne5 (19.
d5 exd5) 19... Rc7 20. Rc3 $14 {and White is better, but Black is quite solid.}
) 18. a5 $1 $16 {Now White's attack plays itself.} Be7 19. Nc4 {[%cal Gc4e5]} (
{My computer likes} 19. Rc4 $5 Nca6 20. Nc2 $40 {but the move in the game is
pretty strong as well.}) 19... Rxd4 ({After} 19... f6 {White decides the game
with} 20. a6 $1 b6 (20... Ncxa6 21. Na5 Nc7 22. Rc4 Qf8 23. Bd2 $18) 21. Nxb6
$1 axb6 22. Rxc6 Ka8 23. Rc4 {with a winning position.}) 20. Ne5 Rf8 21. a6 $1
$18 {Now White is developing a crushing attack.} b6 22. Qc3 {There were two
more winning continuations:} (22. Rxc6 f6 23. Rxb6+ $1 (23. Bxd4 Qxd4 24. Rxc7
Kxc7 25. Ng6 $18) 23... axb6 24. Nc6+ Nxc6 25. Qxb6+ Kc8 26. Qxc6 {[%csl Gc8]})
(22. Ra4 c5 23. Bxd4 Qxd4 24. Rxb4 Qxe5 25. Rxb6+ axb6 26. Qxb6+ Kc8 27. Rd1
$18) 22... c5 23. Bxd4 $6 ({The immediate} 23. Ra4 $1 {would have won,
